For over 4 YEARS I had a horrible time getting my body under control. 
Side effects of birth control, stress, and exhausting my adrenals took a toll on me and parts of my career.
I cut to 135 for Contenders Series and I was back to 157lbs THE NEXT DAY.
I'm fortunate to have gained knowledge throughout the years from dieticians, books, research, and education to get my body back. I've been able to sit at a leaner mass. I'm able to sleep throughout the night instead of my 3am insomnia. I don't feel like sh** every day.
It's unfortunate I couldn't be this way sooner, but I'm blessed to be where I am and for what's to come in my future.

Anywhoosies... who wants to see me fight April 15th? 😬😏🫢

I can't pistol squat on my own. 

My goal is to fix that. 

Why is this important? 

- Because it's something I can't do, and that bothers me. I'm perfectly capable of pistol squatting if I keep working at it. I'm stubborn, and I can do anything I set my mind to. 
Moral here: Do sh** you suck at, and it will become a strength; not a weakness. All it takes is time and effort. Go do hard things. Face something that makes you uncomfortable until it's comfortable. 🌱 🍭💛.

I remember so much about this fight. I tore my ACL and meniscus in the 1st round and kept fighting through the whole thing. I felt like this fight was going to get me to the big league, but that injury threw a curve ball in my plans.
This was one of many times I felt God and life was testing me. But I was relentless and met my first goal in the end. It was a shame to be cut short, but the break to heal and reasses was just what I needed.
We always have a choice; keep going or change directions.
What road is worth the trials and tribulations? The tears? The heartbreak? Being told you're selfish for consuming so much time in the gym and your self-care; your mental escape.

My heart aches not being able to have that next chance; that next fight to see what I'm capable of doing and how much I've grown. 
I'm a hard worker; a go getter.
I love this stuff. I don't feel like I've completed my destination yet. I'm not satisfied. The days, weeks, months pass by so fast now. I can hear the clock ticking and my time is running out. My heart yearns for something more and it's out there. 💛🍭

I have an announcement to make. Have a good day.

I get a lot of shit from a couple of ppl for not running or getting "road work" in. It's not that I don't like running. I used to love it. My body just gets jacked up after doing it. 
So, I use the airdyne instead. 

There are many ways to increase your stamina. 

"A training program designed to improve maximal aerobic power must overload the circulatory system and stress the oxidative capacities of skeletal muscles." -fancy exercise physiology book

All in all, we're improving our VO2 max and lactate threshold. Swim, bike, run..whatever.

Overall, the best way to get in shape for your sport is to do your sport. Runners run, swimmers swim, fighters fight. In my case, the bike is a lot more forgiving on my body than running, and I'm still kicking my ass doing it. I don't see a problem here. 

Thoughts?
.
.
.
.

I've accumulated 5 belts over my MMA career. Each one as important as the next. 25 minutes to test your abilities and make something of yourself.
🌱Blood
🌱Sweat
🌱Tears
🌱Heartbreak
🌱Disappointment 
🌱Set back
🌱Change
These gave periods of growth. 
The definition of success does not lie in these belts, but the grit to overcome adversity and overcome the hard times in between.
Don't strive to be the best among your peers. Be the best of you. 
This stuff never came naturally for me. I think that's why I loved it so much.
💛And this heart.
💛This heart is strong. 
💛This heart is capable. 
💛This heart will always strive for the next destination. On and off the matts.

Whatever you do with your life, do it with full intent and embrace all it gives you.

"In the end all that matters is how you challenge your chaos".-Witcher

.
.
.

Do other female athletes feel the way I feel?

What will it profit a man to gain the whole world but lose his soul.
THIS. HIT. SO. DEEP.
.
.
I've struggled my entire fight career to understand fame over truth. Truth as in staying true to MY identity. 
I have always wanted to be popular, and being popular meant I would be more "successful" and by success that's fame and fortune ($$$).
It's hard not to fall in the grasp of selling sexual content in return for fame and popularity and to make some money. So many athletes are doing this and making bank! Congrats to them, truly. 
But I feel like I am losing my identity if I fall to this path. I am losing what I stand for if I go this route.
Do I want to feel beautiful and strong and feminine in my masculine sport? Yes, of course. But man.. the line is fine, and the struggle is REAL.
For me, that's my coaching and teaching position. What is it all worth? I'm more than a body and more than an athlete.

At the end of the day, I need to remind myself that my hard work, dedication, and truth to what I stand behind is what makes me successful. Doing things that are tough and pushing to conquer those things will make me successful. And seeing my students grow and become bright, brilliant, capable adults will make me successful. I've done and accomplished so much compared to the average. I am successful. I am succeeding.

There are people in life who care about you, but don't understand your dreams. There are also people in life that just don't want you to succeed because they are jealous, envious, lazy, or just don't want to put in the work and want you on that level.
Regardless of the situation, we need to focus on OUR paths and goals and not worry about what other people think or say. And if you're like me; I love some good recognition. But we still need to focus on what WE feel are accomplishments to ourselves and not what others feel your accomplishments are.
